f   Kampen   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","English (Essex, of Norman origin): variant of   Campion   or <b>Campain</b>. The latter is a habitational name from any of several places in Pas-de-Calais and elsewhere in France named Campagne, or from a Norman form of a habitational name from Champagne in northeastern France.","Americanized form of Norwegian   Kampen  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Campaine was born in 1272, in France. She married Sir Arnald de Brocas in 1290, in Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1298, in Gascogne, France, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1272–1298":"1272–1298","1266–1314":"1266–1314","1290–1365":"1290–1365","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","1298–Male":"1298–Surnud","1314":"1314","about 1292":"umbes 1292","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1365":"1365","1266":"1266","1298":"1298","1272":"1272","about 1298":"umbes 1298","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Gascogne, France":"Gascogne, Prantsusmaa","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1272–1298":"1272–1298","1266–1314":"1266–1314","1290–1365":"1290–1365","1292–Male":"1292–Kuollut","1298–Male":"1298–Kuollut","1314":"1314","about 1292":"noin 1292","about 1290":"noin 1290","1365":"1365","1266":"1266","1298":"1298","1272":"1272","about 1298":"noin 1298","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Gascogne, France":"Gascogne, Ranska","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"1272–1298":"1272–1298","12